    38	| "2.5×" (unicode) | "2.5x" (ASCII letter x) |
    39	| "red/yellow/green" / "R/Y/G" / "stoplight" / "traffic-light" indicators | "coaching threshold tiers" / "tiered status indicators" / "tiered indicators" |
    40	| Emoji color codes (🟢🟡🟠🔴) anywhere | Words only ("Low" / "Medium" / "High") |
    41	| "Color guidance for X:" | "X definitions:" |
    42	| Casual abbreviations of any kind | Spell out |
    43	| "Doc B's structure" | "the document's structure" |
    44	
    45	Avoid casual or AI-flavored phrasing:
    46	- "Stating it up front matters because" → "We state it up front because"
    47	- "Recommendation attributes" → "The recommendation attributes" (don't drop articles)
    48	- "Configuration is straightforward" — fine
    49	- "It's a good fit" — too casual; prefer "It fits the merged company's situation"
    50	
    51	## Voice and tone
    52	
    53	These rules carry forward from earlier conversations and are non-negotiable.
    54	
    55	**Reconciliation principle (verbatim, do not modify):**
    56	
    57	> Where the two companies converge, the path is clear. Where they diverge, the recommendation leans toward the approach whose context — operational footprint, customer mix, organizational scale, or strategic priorities — most closely matches the merged company's situation. The recommendation is never about which approach is "better"; it is about which direction the merged company is best positioned to operate from.
    58	
    59	**Tone rules:**
    60	
    61	1. **No comparative judgment language.** Never "more sophisticated," "more mature," "stronger," "weaker," "where their thinking was sharper," "lacks," "fails to," etc.
    62	2. **Attribute approaches to context.** "KBM's approach reflects [their California sales motion / their relationship-led pipeline / their goal of consolidating activity]." "Pivot's approach reflects [their divisional structure / their MillerKnoll-Certified position / their in-house operations footprint]."
    63	3. **Recommendations are forward-looking.** "Operating from [Company]'s framework positions the merged company well because [context-based reasoning]." Not "[Company] got it right."
    64	4. **No advocacy or political commentary.** No "would do real damage to morale," "doesn't care strongly," "where their thinking was sharper." No internal-drafting commentary about which leadership team gets surprised.
    65	5. **No self-deprecating quotes from BRDs.** Even if a company described its own pain colorfully (e.g., KBM's "poo in, poo out"), don't surface those phrases in the unification doc. Reflecting them back to the team is unnecessary and risks landing wrong.
    66	6. **Both companies are credited.** Each section's "Recommendation summary" or "Net read" paragraph names what each company contributes to the merged-company outcome, framed positively for both.
    67	
    68	## Style and grammar
    69	
    70	- **Singular pronoun agreement** for "the company" — *it / its*, not *they / their*. ("Each company entered Orion implementation with established business processes shaped by how each operated at the time.")
    71	- **Comma after introductory clauses.** ("Originally framed around Construction Solutions, but explicitly broadened in the Feb 2026 review session...")
    72	- **Active where possible.** "We state it up front because" not "Stating it up front matters because."
    73	- **Em-dash (—) for parenthetical asides**, with spaces on either side.
    74	- **Section references** use § (U+00A7) — do not write "section" in body text when referencing.
    75	- **Em-dash, en-dash, hyphen** — em-dash for breaks, hyphen for compound words; avoid en-dash unless representing a range.
    76	
    77	## Per-area section template
    78	
    79	Verbatim from Chris-edited Doc Zero §6:
    80	
    81	```
    82	3.0X — [Process Area]
    83	  Decision density:    [Low / Medium / High + one-line headline]
    84	  Source coverage:     [What KBM and Pivot evidence is available]
    85	
    86	  3.0X.1  How each company approaches [process area] today
    87	  3.0X.2  Where the two companies align
    88	  3.0X.3  Where the two companies differ
    89	  3.0X.4  Cross-area dependencies
    90	  3.0X.5  Recommendation summary
    91	  3.0X.6  Decisions for the leadership team
    92	  3.0X.7  Open questions / inputs needed
    93	```
    94	
    95	Plus a header table with: Decision density, Source coverage, KBM source path, Pivot source path.
    96	
    97	## Divergence (D-X) entry pattern
    98	
    99	Each in §3.0X.3 follows this exact structure:
   100	
   101	```
   102	### D-N. [Title — capability or design choice]
   103	
   104	**Source:** [KBM REQ-IDs from BRD with section reference]; [Pivot REQ-IDs from BRD with section reference]; [transcript references where applicable]
   105	
   106	**KBM's approach.** [Neutral description with attribution to KBM's context]
   107	
   108	**Pivot's approach.** [Neutral description with attribution to Pivot's context]
   109	
   110	**Recommendation for the merged company.** [Forward-looking, context-attributed, naming what each company contributes when both are involved]
   111	
   112	**Decision for the leadership team.** [Explicit decision, with default recommendation]
   113	```
   114	
   115	For decisions with sub-parts (e.g., D-3 has 3a / 3b / 3c), use a decisions list:
   116	
   117	```
   118	**Decisions for the leadership team.**
   119	
   120	- (Na) [...] *Recommended default: yes.*
   121	- (Nb) [...] *Recommended default: confirm at session.*
   122	- (Nc) [...] *Recommended default: yes.*
   123	```
   124	
   125	## Decisions table format
   126	
   127	In §3.0X.6:
   128	
   129	```
   130	| # | Decision | Default | Reference |
   131	|---|---|---|---|
   132	| 1 | [Decision text] | Yes | D-1 |
   133	| 2a | [Decision text] | Yes | D-2a |
   134	| 2b | [Decision text] | Confirm at session | D-2b |
   135	```
   136	
   137	Always include a footer line:
   138	
   139	> N decisions: X with default-yes recommendations and Y requiring leadership-team input during the working session.
   140	
   141	Math must reconcile against the table.
   142	
   143	## Cross-area dependencies pattern
   144	
   145	Items decided in another area but surfacing here go in §3.0X.4 with this table:
   146	
   147	```
   148	| Dependency | Where it surfaced in [Area] | Where it's decided |
   149	|---|---|---|
   150	| **[Dependency name]** | [Source ref] | **[Other Area (§3.0X)]** — [one-line why it lives there] |
   151	```
   152	
   153	Do not duplicate the decision in both areas. Cross-reference only.
   154	
   155	## Source citation rules
   156	
   157	Every divergence cites:
   158	- KBM REQ IDs with file path and section number, e.g., `KBM REQ-016 (BRD_CRM_v1.0.md §5)`
   159	- Pivot REQ IDs with file path, e.g., `Pivot REQ-3.01.01 (CRM.md §3.01)`
   160	- Transcript references where the source is a recorded session, e.g., `Pivot Feb 2026 review session`
   161	
   162	If a company's BRD does not address a specific capability, say so explicitly: *"Pivot's CRM BRD does not specifically address [capability]"* — not silence.
   163	
   164	## Configuration carryover (§3.0X.7)
   165	
   166	Pattern:
   167	
   168	```
   169	| Item | KBM-side built? | Pivot-side built? | Action for merged company |
   170	|---|---|---|---|
   171	| [Capability] | [State, e.g., "In progress (early Realize)"] | [State] | [Action, with reference to D-N] |
   172	```
   173	
   174	Use "Specified" not "Spec'd."
   175	
   176	## Open questions (§3.0X.8)
   177	
   178	Numbered list of:
   179	1. Items genuinely unknown that depend on leadership-team input
   180	2. Cross-section dependencies that resolve in other process areas
   181	3. Items raised in transcripts but not yet integrated into BRDs
   182	
   183	Do not include internal drafting commentary about how the document might be received.
   184	
