   237	## 3.02.5 Recommendation summary
   238	
   239	The merged-company CRM playbook in shorthand:
   240	
   241	- **Pipeline:** Pivot's 4-stage weighted model plus a Commit Forecast view at the Closing+ stage filter
   242	- **Opportunity discipline:** Mandatory creation with required-field validation
   243	- **Activity discipline:** Tiered model (required for New / Developing reps; flexible for established reps); universal email auto-capture via SuperSync
   244	- **Hierarchy:** Two-dimensional — division (Pivot) + geography (KBM); internal referral attribution captured
   245	- **Relationship model:** Pivot's multi-company / multi-contact + soft influencer reminders + KBM's role taxonomy
   246	- **Visibility:** Rep-level "owned opportunities" default; hierarchical visibility above
   247	- **GP discipline:** Pivot's framework as structural baseline (target + MillerKnoll mix + erosion across stages)
   248	- **Cross-division referrals:** Pivot's workflow with real-time alerts
   249	- **RFP:** Combined model — Kanban Work Board + early creation + volume tracking
   250	- **Coaching:** Pivot's 2.5× pipeline multiplier with tiered coaching indicators
   251	- **Forecast accuracy:** Tracked per-user, surfaced on manager dashboards
   252	- **Data hygiene:** Standard Orion duplicate detection and merge
   253	
   254	Net read: the merged CRM combines design choices that fit the merged company's situation. Pivot's contributions reflect their divisional sales structure, MillerKnoll-Certified position, and broader operational scope (pipeline model, hierarchy, GP framework, multi-company relationship model, coaching multiplier). KBM's contributions reflect their focus on data discipline and rep-level orientation (mandatory opportunity creation, role taxonomy depth, owned-opportunity visibility, RFP volume tracking, forecast accuracy tracking). The merged company benefits from both.
